description.para:
Preparation of the dataset for GBIF publication used as source the geographic layer in shapefile format. The data layer was a vector layer containing polygons with various sizes. The following steps were performed:
- Intersected the layer with the EEA reference grid (10km);
- Created a joinID column with the row numbers;
- Calculated the WKTs for each polygon in the original (EPSG:3035) projection;
- Calculated the centroids for each polygon in both WGS84 and the original (EPSG:3035) projection.;
- Calculated the distance of the centroids to the farthest point in the envolving polygon (coordinate accuracy) in both WGS84 and the original (EPSG:3035) projection.;
- Used the centroids (in the original projection) with intersect to get the marine regions from (Marine regions (ETRS) 10x10km grid) http://cdr.eionet.europa.eu/help/habitats_art17/Reporting2019 ;
- Produced another shapefile by clipping it with the dissolved biogeographic regions obtained from BiogeoRegions2016_shapefile.zip https://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/data/biogeographical-regions-europe-3 ;
- Calculated the inside centroids of the clipped layer;
- Used the inside centroids (with intersect) to get the biogeographical regions from the previously mentioned layer;
- Joined the results obtained from the clipped layer to the original layer via the joinID;
- For polygons that possessed both a marine a biogeographical region, the appropriate one was chosen based on the species on the polygon and the PT_species_reports.xml obtained from http://cdr.eionet.europa.eu/pt/eu/art17/envuc2hfw/index_html?&page=3 (which I converted into a csv). As such, similarly placed polygons can have different regions.;
- All species/regions combos were cross referenced with the XML, as if the species did not have the corresponding region, it was changed to the correct match (happened in frontier zones)1;
- Used the WGS84 centroids to extract the locations from the CAOP2020;
- exported to csv and reinterpreted attributes matching to DwC standard terms.
